<DocLayout title="How We Work" description="Human-directed, AI-collaborated — the AEGIS Initiative's methodology for governance-first AI security.">
  <h1>How We Work</h1>

  <section>
    <h2>Human-Directed, AI-Collaborated</h2>
    <p>
      The AEGIS Initiative practices what it preaches. We build governance
      frameworks for AI systems, and we use AI systems under governance in our
      own work. The operating model is simple:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Humans decide.</strong> All governance decisions, architectural choices, policy positions, and editorial judgments are made by humans.</li>
      <li><strong>AI assists.</strong> AI tools draft, research, generate code, and analyze — always under human direction and review.</li>
      <li><strong>Transparency is mandatory.</strong> We disclose our use of AI tools openly. Every publication carries attribution.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>Open by Default</h2>
    <p>
      AEGIS specifications, governance documents, and research are published
      openly under permissive licenses. Our code is open source. Our threat
      models are public. Our constitutional articles are versioned and citeable
      with DOIs.
    </p>
    <p>
      We believe that governance frameworks only work if they can be inspected,
      criticized, and improved by the community they serve. Closed governance
      is an oxymoron.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>Standards Engagement</h2>
    <p>
      We don't build in isolation. The AEGIS Initiative actively engages with
      standards bodies and policy organizations to ensure our work aligns with
      and contributes to the broader governance landscape:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>NIST</strong> — AI Risk Management Framework submissions and alignment</li>
      <li><strong>IEEE</strong> — Peer-reviewed publications on constitutional governance architecture</li>
      <li><strong>NCCoE</strong> — AI agent identity, authorization, and governance collaboration</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Our goal is not to replace existing standards but to complement them with
      enforceable, runtime-level governance that turns principles into
      deterministic constraints.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>Development Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      The AEGIS ecosystem is maintained across 11 repositories, each with a
      clear scope and dedicated focus. All work follows these conventions:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>All changes via pull request with review</li>
      <li>Conventional commits (<code>feat:</code>, <code>docs:</code>, <code>chore:</code>, <code>fix:</code>)</li>
      <li>CI checks required before merge</li>
      <li>Dual licensing: CC-BY-SA-4.0 for specifications, Apache 2.0 for code</li>
      <li>All specifications citeable with DOIs via Zenodo</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</DocLayout>
